{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584845"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:58:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:58:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14819"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14819","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14819"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7510"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79607"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7510"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14819"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64911"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"12080"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18362"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18365"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27222"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79607","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79607"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring cell division, the final stage involves separation of the cytoplasm to form two distinct daughter cells.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures is primarily responsible for cytoplasmic division in animal cells?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cell plate","Centrosome","Contractile ring","Mitotic spindle","Nuclear envelope"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Econtractile ring\u003C/strong\u003E is the key structure responsible for cytokinesis in animal cells. It forms at the cell equator and consists of actin and myosin filaments that contract to create a cleavage furrow, ultimately separating the two daughter cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe process is different in plant cells, where a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecell plate\u003C/strong\u003E is the structure used during cytokinesis, formed by vesicles containing cell wall materials.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Enuclear envelope\u003C/strong\u003E reforms around the daughter nuclei but does not participate in cytoplasmic division. The \u003Cstrong\u003Emitotic spindle\u003C/strong\u003E separates chromosomes during mitosis but does not directly participate in cytokinesis. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ecentrosome\u003C/strong\u003E organises microtubules during mitosis but is not involved in the physical separation of daughter cells.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cytokinesis is the physical division of the cytoplasm following nuclear division","A contractile ring of actin and myosin filaments forms at the cleavage furrow to separate daughter cells"],"references":["Alberts B, Bray D, Johnson A, Lewis J, Raff M, Roberts K, et al. Cell communities: tissues, stem cells, and cancer. Essential cell biology, 4th New York Edition: Garland Science; 2018.","Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64911"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14819"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64911","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64911"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T10:50:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T10:50:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data"